The concentration dependent absorption and PL spectra of the GQDs are given in Fig. 2 . On increasing the concentration of GQDs the absorbance and PL intensity increases. The UV–vis absorption spectrum of GQDs shows a shoulder in the UV at 320 nm and a weak absorption tail in the visible region (panel A). The excitation spectrum of PL (ESPL) on monitoring the emission at 430 nm wavelength shows two peaks at 255 nm and 315 nm, respectively. These electronic transitions respectively, are from σ and π molecular orbitals of sp2 triple carbenes to lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (
π *
) [18]. The PL peak is observed at 430 nm (2.88 eV). The excitation dependent PL of GQD is shown in panel C. It is seen that at longer wavelength excitation, a very weak red shifted PL is observed. This observation is similar to that reported in the literature [18].

To elucidate the kinetics of the emission processes, the decay curves of F27-GQD system were also measured at 530 nm on excitation at 340 nm (Table 3
                        ). In contrast to the observation at 430 nm, the decay profiles at longer wavelengths follow single exponential behaviour. The observed decay time of F27 (3.75 ns) at 530 nm does not show any significant changes with wavelength. However, on increasing the GQD concentration, the decay curves show a small increase in the time constant even though the decay remains single exponential (Fig. 8
                        ). The apparent increase in the lifetime of F27 in the mixture at higher concentrations is assigned to the presence of the slower rate constant of red shifted emission of vdW complex formed between F27 and GQDs.
